The paper deals with algorithmic aspects of Tverberg's theorem, which is a well-known result in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the complexity of finding Tverberg partitions in various convexity spaces, which involves combinatorial and discrete mathematics. Hence, cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) are also likely sub-categories. The paper also presents efficient algorithms for certain special classes of graphs, which falls under cs.GT (Graph Theory). Finally, the paper discusses probabilistic algorithms, which involves randomized algorithms and complexity theory, and hence cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is also a likely sub-category.
